File: platform/mcp-server/src/browser-tools/enable-network-capture.ts, lines 44-53.

Currently `state.activeNetworkCaptures.add(args.tabId)` runs on line 52, AFTER `await dispatchToExtension(...)`. If the dispatch times out (30s default) but the extension actually succeeded in enabling capture, `activeNetworkCaptures` won't include the tabId. This causes:
1. `export-har.ts` rejects with 'Network capture is not active' (line 195 checks `state.activeNetworkCaptures.has(args.tabId)`)
2. The CDP debugger session on that tab is orphaned — never cleaned up

Fix: Move `state.activeNetworkCaptures.add(args.tabId)` BEFORE the dispatch, or wrap in try/finally:
```typescript
handler: async (args, state) => {
  state.activeNetworkCaptures.add(args.tabId);
  try {
    const result = await dispatchToExtension(state, 'browser.enableNetworkCapture', {
      tabId: args.tabId,
      ...(args.maxRequests !== undefined ? { maxRequests: args.maxRequests } : {}),
      ...(args.urlFilter !== undefined ? { urlFilter: args.urlFilter } : {}),
      ...(args.maxConsoleLogs !== undefined ? { maxConsoleLogs: args.maxConsoleLogs } : {}),
      ...(args.maxWsFrames !== undefined ? { maxWsFrames: args.maxWsFrames } : {}),
    });
    return result;
  } catch (err) {
    // If dispatch fails definitively (not timeout), clean up the optimistic add
    state.activeNetworkCaptures.delete(args.tabId);
    throw err;
  }
};
```

Actually, the simpler correct approach: keep the add after the await (current position), but ALSO add in a catch-rethrow where we DON'T delete. The real issue is the timeout case — if it times out, the extension may have succeeded. The safest fix is to just always add to the set after the dispatch call, but in a finally block:
```typescript
handler: async (args, state) => {
  const result = await dispatchToExtension(state, 'browser.enableNetworkCapture', { ... });
  state.activeNetworkCaptures.add(args.tabId);
  return result;
};
```
This is actually the current code. The issue is that on timeout, the error propagates and the add never runs. The fix: wrap in try/finally and always add, then let the error propagate. disableNetworkCapture already handles the case where capture wasn't actually started (extension returns success even if debugger isn't attached).

File: platform/mcp-server/src/browser-tools/analyze-site/index.ts, lines 954-961 (catch block) and 1032-1039 (finally block).

When `browser.getNetworkRequests` fails (line 954 catch), the catch block dispatches `browser.disableNetworkCapture` (line 957) and deletes from `activeNetworkCaptures` (line 961). Then the finally block (line 1034-1035) also dispatches `browser.disableNetworkCapture` and deletes from `activeNetworkCaptures`. The second dispatch goes to the extension which will error (debugger already detached), wasting a dispatch round-trip.

Fix: Add a `let captureDisabled = false;` flag before the try block. In the Step 6 catch block, set `captureDisabled = true` after disabling. In the finally block, guard the disableNetworkCapture call:
```typescript
finally {
  if (!captureDisabled) {
    try {
      await dispatchToExtension(state, 'browser.disableNetworkCapture', { tabId });
    } catch { /* ... */ }
    state.activeNetworkCaptures.delete(tabId);
  }
  // closeTab still runs unconditionally
  try {
    await dispatchToExtension(state, 'browser.closeTab', { tabId });
  } catch { /* ... */ }
}
```

Alternatively, remove the disableNetworkCapture from the catch block entirely and let the finally block handle all cleanup. This is simpler and the finally block already handles errors gracefully.

File: platform/mcp-server/src/browser-tools/analyze-site/detect-apis.ts, lines 378-393.

The algorithm at line 386 selects based on `depth > bestDepth` first, only breaking ties by count. This means a prefix at depth 6 shared by 2 endpoints beats a prefix at depth 5 shared by 20 endpoints. The comment says 'Prefer deeper prefixes with sufficient coverage' but the code doesn't actually weight coverage.

Fix: Change the comparison to prefer count (coverage) first, using depth only as a tiebreaker:
```typescript
if (count > bestCount || (count === bestCount && depth > bestDepth)) {
  bestDepth = depth;
  bestCount = count;
  bestPrefix = prefix;
}
```

This way, a prefix shared by 5 endpoints always beats one shared by 2, regardless of depth. When counts are equal, the deeper prefix wins (more specific).

Check existing tests in platform/mcp-server/src/browser-tools/analyze-site/detect-apis.test.ts — update any that test the old depth-first behavior. Add a new test case that verifies the coverage-first selection.
